    "26316189": {
      "title": "Sensitivity of fibroblast growth factor 23 measurements in tumor-induced osteomalacia",
      "abstract": "Context: Tumor-induced osteomalacia (TIO) is a paraneoplastic syndrome of hypophosphatemia, decreased renal phosphate reabsorption, normal or low serum 1,25-dihydryxyvitamin-D concentration, myopathy, and osteomalacia. Fibroblast growth factor 23 (FGF23) is a phosphaturic protein overexpressed in tumors that cause TIO and is, at least partly, responsible for the manifestations of TIO. Objective: The objective of this study was to determine the sensitivity of FGF23 measurements in TIO. Design: FGF23 concentrations were measured on stored samples with three ELISAs. Setting: This study was conducted at subspecialty referral centers. Patients: Twenty-two patients with suspected TIO, 13 with confirmed tumors, were studied. Interventions: There were no interventions in this study. Main Outcome Measure: FGF23 concentration was the main outcome measure of this study. Results: Elevated FGF23 concentrations were detected using the Immunotopics C-terminal assay in 16 of 22 TIO patients (for a sensitivity of 73%), th..."
    }
